          intro: 'In an open economy, fiscal and monetary policy affect exchange rates as well as domestic spending. Expansionary fiscal policy financed by borrowing raises demand for loanable funds or reduces its supply in the standard model, increasing the domestic real interest rate. The higher return attracts foreign capital, raises demand for the domestic currency, causes appreciation, and reduces net exports. This exchange-rate effect partially offsets the initial aggregate-demand expansion and is sometimes called international crowding out.',
          introZh: '开放经济中，财政与货币政策既影响国内支出，也影响汇率。借款融资的扩张性财政政策在标准模型中提高可贷资金需求或减少供给，使国内实际利率上升。更高回报吸引外国资本，提高本币需求，使本币升值并减少净出口。这一汇率效应部分抵消最初的总需求扩张，有时称为国际挤出。',
          model: 'Expansionary monetary policy lowers domestic interest rates in the short run, encouraging capital outflow and reducing foreign demand for domestic financial assets. The domestic currency depreciates, net exports rise, and the AD expansion is reinforced. Contractionary monetary policy raises rates, appreciates the currency, and reduces net exports. Changes abroad also transmit: stronger foreign income raises domestic exports and currency demand; higher foreign interest rates pull capital abroad, depreciating the domestic currency. Expected future exchange rates and risk can modify or reverse simple interest-parity predictions.',
